\begin_layout Section*
Course Capstone Solution by Eshed Magali,
 16.7.2025
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The work is made of 2 questions,
 which is how I structure my solution,
 as well.
 However,
 I will do some definitions first.
 Throughout the course,
 we used the big-O notation 
\begin_inset Formula $O(dt)$
\end_inset

 for function orders in terms of a small time interval.
 I find it easier to use the small-o notation.
 A function 
\begin_inset Formula $f\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is considered to be 
\begin_inset Formula $o(x^{n})$
\end_inset

 if:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lim_{x\to0}\frac{f\left(x\right)}{x^{n}}=0
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It will also come in handy to denote that 
\begin_inset Formula $g^{\left[m\right]}\left(x\right)=g(g(\dots g(x)\dots)$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is applied 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 times in total.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Discrete Branching Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A discrete branching process 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{m}$
\end_inset

 is defined with the multiplicity rule:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p_{0} & =q\\
p_{1} & =p_{2}=\dots=p_{n}=\frac{1-q}{n}\\
\forall j & >n\quad p_{j}=0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq1$
\end_inset

 is some natural number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Prove that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{m\to\infty}\mathbb{E}\left[a_{m}\right]=\infty$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Solution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let some 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 I start by assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}=1$
\end_inset

.
 Since this is a 
\emph on
stationary
\emph default
 branching process,
 the solution for any other initial population size will just involve raising the PGF to the power of the initial population,
 and the initial population has no effect on whether the system grows to infinity or not,
 so long as it is positive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have seen in class that for any multiplicity PGF 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 (which includes death,
 as defined above),
 the stationary branching process' PGF at the 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

-th generation,
 denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{m}$
\end_inset

,
 is just:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
H_{m}\left(x\right)=Q^{\left[m\right]}\left(x\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can get the recursion relation for the expectation by deriving this in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and setting 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dH_{m}}{dx}\left(x\right)=\frac{dQ}{dx}\left(Q^{\left[m-1\right]}\left(x\right)\right)\left(\frac{d}{dx}\left(Q^{\left[m-1\right]}\right)\left(x\right)\right)=\frac{dQ}{dx}\left(H_{m-1}\left(x\right)\right)\left(\frac{dH_{m-1}}{dx}\left(x\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And setting 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

 we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbb{E}\left[a_{m}\right]=\frac{dH_{m}}{dx}\left(1\right)=\frac{dQ}{dx}\left(1\right)\mathbb{E}\left[a_{m-1}\right]=\left[\sum_{\nu=0}^{\infty}\nu p_{\nu}\right]\mathbb{E}\left[a_{m-1}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far it is the derivation for the generalized microbial problem from class verbatim,
 from the second lecture of this semester.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now,
 we just need to pop in our multiplicity,
 and prove that there exists some 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 such that the system is supercritical,
 i.e,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}\equiv\sum_{\nu=0}^{\infty}\nu p_{\nu}>1$
\end_inset

.
 The recursion relation will be solved to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{E}\left[a_{m}\right]=\bar{\nu}^{m}$
\end_inset

 (as seen in class),
 which will limit to infinity iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\nu}>1$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{\nu}\left(n\right)=\sum_{\nu=0}^{\infty}\nu p_{\nu}=0\cdot q+\frac{1-q}{n}\sum_{\nu=1}^{n}\nu=\frac{1-q}{n}\frac{n\left(n+1\right)}{2}=\frac{1}{2}\left(1-q\right)\left(n+1\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Choose 
\begin_inset Formula $n=2\left\lceil \frac{1}{1-q}\right\rceil +1$
\end_inset

.
 We know that:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\bar{\nu}\left(n\right) & =\frac{1}{2}\left(1-q\right)\left(2\left\lceil \frac{1}{1-q}\right\rceil +2\right)\\
 & =\left(1-q\right)\left\lceil \frac{1}{1-q}\right\rceil +1-q\\
 & >\frac{1-q}{1-q}+1-q=1+\left(1-q\right)>1
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\square$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Continuous Branching Process
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let a continuous branching process be defined by these per-capita reaction rates:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lambda_{0}\left(n\right) & =\lambda_{0}\\
\lambda_{2}\left(n\right) & =\begin{cases}
\lambda_{2,0}+\frac{a}{n} & n\neq0\\
\lambda_{2,0} & 0
\end{cases}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Well,
 it seems clear that the question means to say that the per-capita rate for dying and giving birth to 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 descendants is 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}\left(n\right)$
\end_inset

.
 It could also have been trying to convey the per-capita rate for a population change of size 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

,
 but that's irrelevent information for this problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It also seems clear that the second rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}\left(n\right)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

 being any specific number is meaningless,
 because a per-capita rate in that case would always be 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

,
 if it is well defined.
 We might as well have written it to be 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The total reaction rate for a population of size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is just:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda\left(n\right)=\lambda_{0}\left(n\right)+\lambda_{2}\left(n\right)=\begin{cases}
\lambda_{0}+\lambda_{2,0}+\frac{a}{n} & n\neq0\\
\lambda_{0}+\lambda_{2,0} & n=0
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Differential equation for the population of size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 be the probability of a population of size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{n}\left(t\right)=\mathbb{P}\left[X_{t}=n\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}$
\end_inset

 being our stochastic process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Solution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will split the cases for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0,1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n>1$
\end_inset

.
 We will look at what happens during 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[t,t+dt\right]$
\end_inset

 and its effects on the probability at 
\begin_inset Formula $t+dt$
\end_inset

,
 using the law of total probability,
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n>1$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a_{n}\left(t+dt\right) & =a_{n}\left(t\right)\left(1-P\left(\text{at least one event with \ensuremath{n} individuals}\right)\right)\\
 & +a_{n+1}\left(t\right)\left(n+1\right)\lambda_{0}\left(n+1\right)dt\\
 & +a_{n-1}\left(t\right)\left(n-1\right)\lambda_{2}\left(n-1\right)dt+o\left(dt\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have to do the forward derivation because of the same kind of problem we encountered in the logistic model when we tried to do the backward derivation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first term here is the probability of no event.
 Just like the logistical problem in class from 19.5.2025 (lecture 8),
 up to first order this can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(\text{at least one event with \ensuremath{n} individuals}\right)=n\lambda\left(n\right)dt+o\left(dt\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And thus we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{da_{n}}{dt}=-n\left(\lambda_{0}+\lambda_{2,0}+\frac{a}{n}\right)a_{n}+a_{n+1}\left(t\right)\left(n+1\right)\lambda_{0}dt+a_{n-1}\left(t\right)\left(n-1\right)\left(\lambda_{2,0}+\frac{a}{n-1}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For 
\begin_inset Formula $n=0$
\end_inset

 we have a simpler version,
 where:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{0}\left(t+dt\right)=a_{0}\left(t\right)+a_{1}\left(t\right)\lambda_{0}dt+o\left(dt\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{da_{0}}{dt}=\lambda_{0}a_{1}\left(t\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

 we have the slightly more complicated version of:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{1}\left(t+dt\right)=a_{1}\left(t\right)\left[1-\left(\lambda_{0}+\lambda_{2,0}+a\right)dt\right]+a_{2}\left(t\right)2\lambda_{0}dt+o\left(dt\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And therefore:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{da_{1}}{dt}=-\left(\lambda_{0}+\lambda_{2,0}+a\right)a_{1}\left(t\right)+2a_{2}\left(t\right)\lambda_{0}+o\left(dt\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I believe this concludes this subsection,
 because we can't really further simplify these equations,
 since they're coupled together.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
PDE for the PGF of the population at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We denote the PGF of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{t}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(x,t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 We can multipliy all the differential equations for 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{n}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{n}$
\end_inset

 and sum over all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 to get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial G}{\partial t}\left(x,t\right) & =\lambda_{0}\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}a_{n+1}\left(t\right)\left(n+1\right)x^{n}+\\
 & -\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}n\left(\lambda_{0}+\lambda_{2,0}+\frac{a}{n}\right)a_{n}\left(t\right)x^{n}\\
 & +\sum_{n=2}^{\infty}\left(n-1\right)a_{n-1}\left(t\right)\left(\lambda_{2,0}+\frac{a}{n-1}\right)x^{n}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first term we deal with like we always do.
 It is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{0}\frac{\partial G}{\partial x}$
\end_inset

.
 The second and third terms we can separate out the usual population-independent rates from the 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{n}$
\end_inset

 terms to get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial G}{\partial t}\left(x,t\right) & =\lambda_{0}\frac{\partial G}{\partial x}\left(x,t\right)\\
 & -\left(\lambda_{0}+\lambda_{2,0}\right)\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}na_{n}\left(t\right)x^{n}\\
 & +\lambda_{2,0}\sum_{n=2}^{\infty}\left(n-1\right)a_{n-1}\left(t\right)x^{n}\\
 & -a\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}a_{n}\left(t\right)x^{n}\\
 & +a\sum_{n=2}^{\infty}a_{n-1}\left(t\right)x^{n}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second term is simply 
\begin_inset Formula $-\left(\lambda_{0}+\lambda_{2,0}\right)x\frac{\partial G}{\partial x}$
\end_inset

 and the third is 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2,0}x^{2}\frac{\partial G}{\partial x}$
\end_inset

.
 So we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial G}{\partial t}\left(x,t\right) & =\frac{\partial G}{\partial x}\left(x,t\right)\left[\left(\lambda_{0}+\lambda_{2,0}x^{2}\right)-\left(\lambda_{0}+\lambda_{2,0}\right)x\right]\\
 & -a\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}a_{n}\left(t\right)x^{n}+a\sum_{n=2}^{\infty}a_{n-1}\left(t\right)x^{n}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first term is similar to the logistic model case,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $q\left(x\right)=\lambda_{0}+\lambda_{2,0}x^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the characteristic polynomial of the multiplicity rates,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\lambda_{0}+\lambda_{2,0}\right)x$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda x$
\end_inset

 ,where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is the no-feedback per-capita reaction rate.
 So this matches our expectation to be similar to the logistic model,
 except with some perturbation given in the last 2 terms.
 Those terms are almost,
 but not quite,
 transferable to be the PGF.
 Instead:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}a_{n}\left(t\right)x^{n}=a\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}a_{n}\left(t\right)x^{n}-aa_{0}\left(t\right)=a\left[G\left(x,t\right)-a_{0}\left(t\right)\right]=a\left[G\left(x,t\right)-G\left(0,t\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And similarly:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a\sum_{n=2}^{\infty}a_{n-1}\left(t\right)x^{n}=a\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}a_{n-1}\left(t\right)x^{n}-axa_{0}\left(t\right)=ax\left[G\left(x,t\right)-a_{0}\right]=ax\left[G\left(x,t\right)-G\left(0,t\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So we can write for the full PDE:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial G}{\partial t}\left(x,t\right)=\frac{\partial G}{\partial x}\left(x,t\right)\left[q\left(x\right)-\Lambda x\right]+a\left(x-1\right)\left[G\left(x,t\right)-G\left(0,t\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finishing this subsection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Explain why this PDE is problematic (is it autonomous?),
 and suggest a condition for which it can be approximated with an autonomous equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This PDE is not autonomous.
 The term 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(0,t\right)$
\end_inset

 is introducing this problem,
 because that's a strict 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 dependence,
 although through a non-local evaluation of the distribution.
 In general,
 equations being non-autonomous isn't strange for us.
 Strictly speaking,
 the stationary branching process problem is actually also non-autonomous because we have a direct dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in it.
 Just like the PDE:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial F}{\partial t}=\frac{\partial F}{\partial x}+x
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is,
 mathematically speaking,
 non-autonomous,
 because it has a strict dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Without context such as to which variable has boundary conditions and which has the initial condition,
 a mathematician can't imbue the PDE with more significance when it non-autonomous in 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 vs non-autonomous in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 So it might seem at first that being non-autonomous isn't something new and problematic,
 but it somewhat is.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here we are non-autonomous in 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

,
 which is much more of real issue,
 because that's the initial condition variable and not the boundary condition variable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem really is that since 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(0,t\right)=a_{0}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 isn't a known function or one we know how to solve for,
 we would not be able to solve the PDE (which is actually quite usual for us not to solve),
 but more crucially,
 if we try to get moments from it by deriving it and setting 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

,
 we would not be rid of the 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(0,t\right)$
\end_inset

 term.
 For example,
 if we try to get the first moment equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial^{2}G}{\partial x\partial t}\left(x,t\right) & =\frac{\partial^{2}G}{\partial x^{2}}\left(x,t\right)\left[q\left(x\right)-\Lambda x\right]+\frac{\partial G}{\partial x}\left(x,t\right)\left[\frac{\partial q}{\partial x}-\Lambda\right]\\
 & +a\left[G\left(x,t\right)-G\left(0,t\right)\right]+a\left(x-1\right)\frac{\partial G}{\partial x}\left(x,t\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And when we set 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

 we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{dM_{1}}{dt} & =\frac{\partial^{2}G}{\partial x\partial t}\left(1,t\right)=\frac{\partial^{2}G}{\partial x^{2}}\left(1,t\right)\left(\cancel{\lambda_{0}+\lambda_{2,0}-\lambda_{0}-\lambda_{2,0}}\right)+M_{1}\left(\lambda_{2,0}-\lambda_{0}\right)+a\left(1-a_{0}\left(t\right)\right)\\
 & =M_{1}\left(\lambda_{2,0}-\lambda_{0}\right)+a\left(1-a_{0}\left(t\right)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Which we can't really use,
 because we don't know 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 It's somewhat similar in terms of it being problematic to when we tried to find a PDE for the meta stable solution in the logistical model,
 but didn't know how to handle the extinction case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
What we need is some condition so that this problem goes away.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can introduce the condition that 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}\left(t\right)$
\end_inset

 is always negligible (compared to 1,
 for example),
 so we can always drop it relative to the terms coming out of 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(x,t\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This can happen.
 For example,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2,0}\gg\lambda_{0}$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G\left(x,0\right)=x^{N_{0}}$
\end_inset

 for some large 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{0}$
\end_inset

,
 the system is supercritical and it would be negligibly unlikely for extinction to occur.
 So this condition can be physically satiable for some cases.
 It can also work even if 
\begin_inset Formula $a<0$
\end_inset

,
 as we'll see in the next section,
 because it does not cause the population to dip in expectation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is the case I will go with,
 because it assumes the least amount of knowledge that still keeps the problem somewhat interesting.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Other Options
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We could also assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\ll\lambda_{2,0}$
\end_inset

,
 but that would make this problem return to be the stationary problem (which isn't autonomous in 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 but is at least autonomous in 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

,
 which is,
 again,
 the important bit).
 However,
 this is less interesting,
 because we already have the solution to that problem from class.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We could also do something a bit more interesting.
 The ODE for 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

 was given above to be:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{da_{0}}{dt}=\lambda_{0}a_{1}\left(t\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}\ll1$
\end_inset

 for all times and throwing it away is somewhat less interesting than maybe saying that for times of interest,
 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}\left(t\right)\sim\lambda_{0}Ct$
\end_inset

 for some (small) constant 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
 This arises if we physically assume 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}$
\end_inset

 is some small and rather constant value during those times.
 This would allow us to actually solve things,
 and is more interesting than setting 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}=0$
\end_inset

 whenever we need to,
 compared to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 This is satiated in similar conditions to the one I chose above,
 it just lets the next order in 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 in,
 which would probably somewhat extend the range of applicability,
 if we pick 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 well.
 Picking 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 would be a problem,
 which is mostly why I wouldn't go with it without some more drill down to estimate it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Derive an ODE for the first moment of the population at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 under your suggested condition
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Well,
 if we assume 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

 is negligible,
 we still have from above:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial^{2}G}{\partial x\partial t}\left(x,t\right) & =\frac{\partial^{2}G}{\partial x^{2}}\left(x,t\right)\left[q\left(x\right)-\Lambda x\right]+\frac{\partial G}{\partial x}\left(x,t\right)\left[\frac{\partial q}{\partial x}-\Lambda\right]\\
 & +a\left[G\left(x,t\right)\cancel{-G\left(0,t\right)}\right]+a\left(x-1\right)\frac{\partial G}{\partial x}\left(x,t\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And setting 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1$
\end_inset

 we still get:
\series bold

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boldsymbol{\frac{dM_{1}}{dt}=M_{1}}\boldsymbol{\left(\lambda_{2,0}-\lambda_{0}\right)+a\left(1\cancel{-a_{0}\left(t\right)}\right)\approx M_{1}\left(\lambda_{2,0}-\lambda_{0}\right)+a}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution for this wasn't required in the question,
 but if we look at it,
 we can see values of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 which risk our assumptions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solution is that of an inhomogeneous ODE,
 and we pick the particular solution to be a constant 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus,
 we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C=-\frac{a}{\lambda_{2,0}-\lambda_{0}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And the full solution is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{1}\left(t\right)=Ae^{\left(\lambda_{2,0}-\lambda_{0}\right)t}-\frac{a}{\lambda_{2,0}-\lambda_{0}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{1}=N_{0}$
\end_inset

 and we get:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=N_{0}+\frac{a}{\lambda_{2,0}-\lambda_{0}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And we get,
 in total:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
M_{1}\left(t\right)=\left(N_{0}+\frac{a}{\lambda_{2,0}-\lambda_{0}}\right)e^{\left(\lambda_{2,0}-\lambda_{0}\right)t}-\frac{a}{\lambda_{2,0}-\lambda_{0}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus,
 even negative values of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 never cause the population to dip down,
 so they pose little additional risk to our assumptions holding.
 It seems that being supercritical in the no-feedback terms and a large enough initial population should indeed suffice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
What would this be with the slightly more complicated version?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we were to take the slightly more interesting case of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}\sim\lambda_{0}Ct$
\end_inset

 for some small 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

,
 we would get a very similar:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dM_{1}}{dt}=M_{1}\left(\lambda_{2,0}-\lambda_{0}\right)+a\left(1-a_{0}\left(t\right)\right)\approx M_{1}\left(\lambda_{2,0}-\lambda_{0}\right)+a\left(1-\lambda_{0}Ct\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Which is still solvable rather easily,
 but introduces this 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 parameter,
 so I still prefer the simpler version above for most purposes.
\end_layout

\end_body
